ce:section.ce:para:
The wound-healing potential of HNE was investigated by analyzing its chemical composition using GC-MS. The results showed that HNE contained 27 compounds, representing 94.7% of the total extract (

                        Table 1
                        ). Among these compounds, six were found to have the highest percentage: germacrene D (19.2%), β-pinene (14.6%), limonene (12.5%), β-cubenene (11.3%), linalool (5.6%), and β-caryophyllene (5.4%). These compounds are known to have antibacterial properties, which are essential for preventing wound infection and promoting wound healing. Germacrene D, β-pinene, and limonene are monoterpenes that have been reported to exhibit antimicrobial activity against various bacteria and fungi (Criollo-Mendoza et al., 2023). β-cubenene, linalool, and β-caryophyllene are sesquiterpenes that have also shown antibacterial and anti-inflammatory effects (Marume et al., 2017). The presence of these compounds in HNE could be the reason for its wound healing properties, as they could interact with the different phases of the wound healing process, such as coagulation, inflammation, proliferation, and remodeling.
